Whose tomb fair Love, and fairer Virtue kept:

All suddenly I saw the Fairy Queen;

At whose approach the soul of Petrarch wept,

And, from thenceforth, those Graces were not seen:

For they this queen attended; in whose stead

Oblivion laid him down on Lauras hearse:

Hereat the hardest stones were seen to bleed,

And groans of buried ghosts the heavens did pierce:

Where Homers spright did tremble all for grief,

And cursed the access of that celestial thief!/CONTENT"	NAME/A Vision upon the Fairy Queen/NAME	AGE/Renaissance/AGE	TYPE/Love/TYPE
AUTHOR/THOMAS CAMPION/AUTHOR	"CONTENT/When thou must home to shades of underground,

